oint for incorporating surgical findings to guide further treatment actions for NSCLC [Data: Entities (215); Relationships (504)]. For instance, transitions from this node to stage-specific entities such as Stage IA (T1 N0) demonstrate how management recommendations (e.g., observation, adjuvant therapy) hinge on intraoperative and pathological assessments. This centrality underlines the importance of multidisciplinary discussions following surgery to determine the appropriate adjuvant therapy or surveillance plan.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Margin status and cancer staging are critical in determining postoperative management.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Detailed differentiation between stages (IA, IB, IIA, IIB, IIIA/IIIB) and margin statuses (positive/R1, R2 vs. negative/R0) strongly influence the recommended next steps, such as reresection, systemic therapy, or observation [Data: Entities (216, 219, 221, 222, 223, 227); Relationships (504, 520, 523, 526, 528, 530, 534)]. For example, positive surgical margins often prompt reresection or adjuvant therapy, whereas negative margins may allow for observation alone, demonstrating the tailored approach required based on pathological findings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Adjuvant systemic therapy (NSCL-E) is a recurrent recommendation for higher-stage or high-risk NSCLC cases.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The entity representing adjuvant systemic therapy (NSCL-E) and its relationship to various disease stages (particularly IIB and IIIA/IIIB) underscore its recognized role in improving outcomes for patients with more advanced or aggressive disease [Data: Entities (225, 215, 227, 223); Relationships (534, 530, 540)]. The protocol suggests adjuvant systemic therapy either sequentially or in combination with other interventions (including chemoradiation), reflecting evidence-based escalation of therapy for patients at increased risk of recurrence.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Reresection, with or without systemic therapy, is proposed for certain margin-positive or recurrent scenarios.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Entities and relationships addressing reresection strategies, such as 'Reresection (preferred) ± systemic therapy', connect with various margin-positive and stage-specific nodes [Data: Entities (220, 218, 222); Relationships (528, 538, 539)]. This pathway recognizes the importance of achieving margin-negative resections where feasible and guides clinicians on when to pursue further surgery versus proceeding directly to adjuvant treatments or observation. The references to category 2B (lower-level evidence recommendations) for some reresection approaches also highlight potential clinical controversy or individualized decision-making.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Observation remains a valid strategy for select patients, mainly at lower stages or with negative margins.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Entities and pathways capture the standard of care whereby patients with early-stage NSCLC and negative margins may be observed without the need for immediate additional intervention post-surgery [Data: Entities (217, 216, 221, 219, 215); Relationships (520, 523, 526, 537)]. Such decisions prioritize minimizing overtreatment and focus on surveillance to detect possible recurrences, balancing benefits and risks based on individual patient factors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Chemoradiation is an option, particularly where surgery alone is insufficient or inoperable disease is encountered.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Both sequential and concurrent chemoradiation appear as alternatives or additions to surgery in the pathways for certain higher-stage patients or when systemic/local control is suboptimal [Data: Entities (228, 229, 225); Relationships (542, 543, 540)]. This reflects modern NSCLC management, integrating multidisciplinary modalities to maximize disease control, especially in non-resectable or high-risk cases.\"\n    }\n  ],